# Read in data

<!-- rnb-text-end -->



<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


# Goal

The goal of the Psychology Department Climate Survey is provide the department with insights into feelings of inclusion and equality (or lack thereof) within the graduate student, postdoc, and research staff population. This information will inform efforts to cultivate an inclusive community that values diverse questions, viewpoints, approaches, and participant samples to foster ingenuity, challenge biases, and promote intellectual growth. Further, this information will inform possible actions to foster individual and collective wellbeing, which is requisite for academic success. 

# Method

In Summer 2019, graduate students, postdoctoral fellows, and research staff were emailed an online link to complete the Climate Survey (a PDF of the survey is available on the Psychology Graduate Students Google Drive in the "Climate Survey" folder). 

The survey included questions about feelings of belonging uncertainty, stereotype threat (i.e., concerns about negative judgement due to  identity), contextual threat (i.e., beliefs and experiences of bias and discrimination), beliefs about collective action (i.e., beliefs that others value increasing inclusivity), and gender dynamics (i.e., concerns about issues surrounding gender identity and harassment). In addition, we collected information concerning participation in the Diversity Committee (i.e., past participation and interest). We asked minimal demographics questions to avoid identifiability within the relatively small sample, emphasizing that these questions were optional.

We received 60 response to the survey. We included optional questions about position in the department (graduate student, postdoc, research staff), gender identity (female, male, other/non-binary), and identity as an underrepresented minority. Among participants who responded, the majority (N = 27) were graduate students, followed by research staff (N = 11), and postdoctoral fellows (N = 7). In terms of gender, approximately twice as many participants identified as female (N = 30) compared to male (N = 16), indicating an imbalance in participation, although it is possible that a larger proportion of the group who did not respond to the demographic questions was male. No one identified their gender as "other/non-binary." Finally, 18 participants identified as an underrepresented minority.

When participants were asked about the frequency with which they wondered "maybe I don't belong" in the Psychology Department and in academia generally, the modal response was "sometimes". Indeed, 50% of students endorsed "sometimes." 

When thinking about the Psychology Department, very few participants reported "never" feeling concerned about belonging (3%). Therefore, having at least some uncertainty about belonging is a typical experience in the department. A greater percentage of participants who identified as underrepresented minorities reported "sometimes" or "frequently" experiencing belonging uncertainty than did students who did not identify as minorities (79% vs. 59%), although the mode for both groups was "sometimes." 

When thinking about academia, no one reported "never" or "always" feeling concerned about belonging. Instead, one third of participants reported "frequently" feeling concerned. Distributions were similar across students who did and did not endorse minority status.

When asked to what extent they _believe_ underrepresented students experience bias or discrimination, the modal response was "somewhat." Distributions were similar based on minority and gender identity. 

When asked how often they had _experienced_ or _witnessed_ bias, discrimination, or unfair treatment, approximately half reported "less than once a month" or more often (mode = "never"). When comparing minority and non-minority participants, a _larger_ percentage of minority participants reported experiencing bias or discrimination "never" than did non-minority participants (50%, mode = "never" vs. 37%, mode = "less than once a month"). When comparing female and male participants,  participants who identified as female experienced or witness bias more frequently than did male participants (63%., mode = "less than once a month" vs. 44%, mode = "never").

I don't know whether this fits under \"climate and diversity\" but I do feel like it exists and has a negative impact on the well-being of students at large."},{"1":"Climate: It can be hard to measure how well one is doing at their job, which can create stress via uncertainty. Diversity: I wouldn't call the department as a whole particularly diverse."},{"1":"'-People don't understand that their actions are discriminatory/hurtful/contribute to a toxic environment. For example, I have heard lab members make transphobic comments and jokes without seemingly any awareness of the impact their words had. \\n-Minority groups are underrepresented in positions of power, e.g., most of the faculty are white."},{"1":"'- resources and logistical support for students from marginalized backgrounds (e.g., money for retreats)\\n- department playing a bigger role in connecting students to mental health resources"},{"1":"1) I think we need a standardized admissions review process across areas, or at least an explicit process that does not change year to year. Currently, it's subject to change based on who's serving on the admissions committee in an area, which opens the door to too much discretion & bias. \\n2) The majority of people working on diversity in the department are women & minority students. Could the department consider incentivizing/rewarding service work like this in order to remove the burden from these groups and/or potentially get other groups involved in the effort."},{"1":"1. The stigma around mental health: I've had many people reveal to me that they are struggling with mental health or have struggled in the past after I've gotten to know them, but they are terrified of that getting out or having that be revealed to their advisor or other professors. Almost anyone will animatedly caution others to guard against anyone, and in particular her/his advisor, ever knowing or seeing that they are struggling, which only adds to people's anxiety and struggle. It is the ultimate taboo in a time when it genuinely feels like you can more openly talk about other minority identities/ experiences and acceptance around these things is improving (e.g. ethnicity, gender, sexual orientation, socioeconomic status, physical disability).\\n2. As much as I love the current professors in Neuro and Cog, efforts need to be made to hire more diverse professors. It helps minority individuals imagine themselves succeeding in the future. Such professors also model successful methods of dealing with the special challenges/prejudice that minority groups face and are forces for making the culture more genuinely accepting. There are too many white males and too many of any one group leads to blindspots. It isn't that they don't deserve to be here as much as a more 'diverse' hire, and I wouldn't advocate for hiring a less-qualified person in order to make the areas more diverse, but I wonder if diverse potential hires only seem incrementally less qualified in some instances because they seem less familiar to those already here or if white male potential hires seem better because they can be more confident in interviews/ interactions or just feel more familiar or like a vaguely 'better fit' for the department due to their similarity to those in charge of hiring. When thinking about candidates pros and cons, make sure you are making decisions based on concrete evidence. Be as exacting about defining why you prefer or don't prefer one candidate over another as you are about defining psychological terms. Consider your biases and ask others, without reprisal, if you seem to be acting in a biased manner.\\n3. Accept that not all trainees will go into academia and don't penalize those that don't wish to or are skeptical. Many trainees that don't wish to go into academia or are skeptical dreamt their whole lives of becoming a professor. They believe in academia and they love research. But they are worried about the increased competition for tenure track positions and the likelihood that they will spend many, many, years taking pay cuts while they prepare for an academic position just to not get one in the end. But they have or want children and what they observe of academic parents doesn't fit with how they want to raise their kids, in part because academia has not changed enough to really accommodate families with two working, ambitious parents. But the combination of their aspirations and their partner's might make pursuing academia impossible or, quite frankly, selfish. But they or their family members have physical or mental disabilities that wouldn't fit well with academia as currently structured. But they see other or greater opportunities for doing good research or working to improve the world outside of academia. These are just a few of the reasons and I think they are reasonable. It seems like some Professors' reflex to any indication that someone doesn't want to go into academia or isn't sure is that that person is wasting their time or taking up a space that should have gone to someone else. They make assumptions and they don't talk to us. We get and sympathize with the fact that Professor's and departments are judged in part by their trainees success in academia, but we have very real and very reasonable concerns as well. And the education we receive and work for isn't wasted if we apply it outside of academia. Talk to us. If we are backing away from academia because we are in some way mistaken about how it could fit into our lives, an open conversation with us might help us navigate those obstacles and stay in academia. As it is, many of us keep quiet about our concerns/ intentions for years and end up going outside of academia because we couldn't be open with our advisors. Everyone suffers under this dynamic.\\n"},{"1":"'-Name of the building as Jordan Hall, after a eugenicist...\\n-Need for students to pay up front for thousands of dollars for research and get paid back months later"},{"1":"I don't think there are any issues. In my opinion, the department does an incredible job of making minorities feel welcomed and part of the community."},{"1":"I don't feel super well positioned to comment on this, but one thing I see that is frustrating to me is disproportionate male representation in more \"technical\" areas of the department. In Cognitive and Neuro, it seems to me the strong majority of faculty, students, and staff are men."},{"1":"1) Almost all-white faculty, new hires have been white men, and all but one faculty of color currently research a topic having to do with racial diversity, which is itself tokenizing.\\n2) Lack of quantitative faculty and resources make people with non-math backgrounds feel left out, looked down on, and unable to catch up.\\n3) Lack of real valuing of students' mental health, lack of community events and spaces, and the only check-in's with advisors about personal well-being take place once a year or less often."},{"1":"1) One issue is social support and professional development for RCs. RCs, like students, often move from far away to work at Stanford and are dropped into a completely unfamiliar life. Unlike students, we do not have the built-in social groups of cohorts or classmates; we don't necessarily meet with professors often or work with many people in the department; we don't necessarily have our own work that others can provide feedback on or get invested in (in any way). It's very easy for RCs to feel like an outsider, because we are so closely adjacent to many tightknit groups (working and social), yet separate from them. We are here to support the work of students and professors - and sometimes that can feel quite othering and belittling. 2) I've heard of professors planning on non-white employees as \"temp\" until they could receive diversity funds and then make them permanent, though they could have made them permanent staff sooner. 3) We should do more to engage with just volunteering / RA management practices. I know of many labs and students that expect volunteers to commit to 20+ hours per week, and they argue that its okay because \"people are willing.\" This at best perpetuates opportunity differences, and really exacerbates them. This is shameful."},{"1":"Interactions between students and advisors- I don't know how to solve this, but it sounds like many students feel awful about themselves after interactions with advisors in a way that not only reduces well-being, but actually reduces productivity. I think this reflects a larger issue in academia where professors are never taught how to manage people effectively.  \\n\\nThe individualistic culture of research- Not only is this an isolating component of the department, but I think this is particularly damaging to underrepresented groups.\\n\\nThe pipeline- there are simply not as many qualified diverse candidates as there could be.  I think Stanford is behind many other schools in attempting to improve this pipeline at all stages and ensure diverse students are moving through the academic ladder."},{"1":"1. Gender inclusion in the neuro area, which also extends to the general climate. It can feel alienating and hostile at times, even though I doubt anyone (except for Brian Wandell!) is trying to do that. \\n\\nTreatment of lab managers and RAs. There are labs in the department that routinely mismanage/mistreat RAs and lab managers. I'm thinking especially about the Gross lab, but I'd guess there are others. I don't know that anyone is sticking up for them. This is upsetting, especially considering that this is an important path for many people from less advantaged backgrounds to gain experience before applying for graduate school. But they're also just really important members of our community (that make everyone else's work possible) that we need to be taking better care of."},{"1":"1. I feel that I connected with people in my cohort and area and found a strong group of friends in the department who I can draw on for social support, but I don't think that is true for everyone. What about the students who seem to have fallen through the cracks socially? What about those who may have different ideological views than the rest of their area or cohort? It seems that there are some students who totally disengage (e.g. stop coming to department events, such as those held during prospectives weekend, and stop coming to area talks, such as social lab). How can we reach those students once they have disengaged? I feel this is particularly modeled by faculty members: when faculty members don't show up to those events (particularly those with joint appointments), it makes total sense that their graduate students would disengage and stop going to those events as well.\\n2. The problem of interrupting, talking over others, and asking aggressive questions during public talks makes those talks spaces where students don't feel their ideas are welcome. It may be subtle, but it is insidious: when faculty members interrupt speakers - particularly if those speakers are women or people of color - it signals who gets to talk and who gets given time to finish what they're saying before they're interrupted. When certain people monopolize time in these public talks without a regard for others in the room, it signals that they are thinking only of themselves without a regard for the climate, culture, or norms they might be creating."},{"1":"Cost of living (funding relative to housing)\\nUp-front expenses for incoming grad students\\nResistance to acknowledge and confront systemic issues"}],"options":{"columns":{"min":{},"max":[10],"total":[1]},"rows":{"min":[10],"max":[10],"total":[19]},"pages":{}}}

Among participants who responded when asked about participation in Paths to PhD, the majority of student had participated (47%), suggesting this event has been successful in recruiting volunteers. Among participants who had not yet served on the Diversity Committee, 37% reported they were interested in serving in the future. Of the 59% who responded they were not interested, the model explanation was "I am too busy to serve on committees."
